Why Tree-Based Methods? Real-World Context

The Limitations We’ve Seen:

  • Linear regression: Assumes additive, linear relationships
  • Logistic regression: Linear decision boundaries
  • k-NN: Makes predictions but can’t explain “why” (black box)
  • Real world: Complex interactions, non-linear patterns, need for interpretable rules

What if relationships look like this?

  • High income + Low debt → Approve loan
  • Young age + High risk job → Higher insurance premium
  • Chest pain + Abnormal stress test → High heart disease risk

Enter Decision Trees:

  • Human-like reasoning: Series of yes/no questions
  • Automatic interactions: No need to specify X₁ × X₂ terms
  • Mixed data types: Handle numerical and categorical naturally
  • Interpretable rules: Can explain decisions to stakeholders (major advantage over k-NN)
  • Global model: One set of rules for all predictions (vs k-NN’s local neighborhoods)

This Week’s Journey: Today we learn how trees work, then build toward ensemble methods that combine many trees for superior performance while maintaining interpretability.

Motivating Example: Predicting Baseball Salaries

Let’s predict baseball player salaries using just two predictors: Years (experience) and Hits (performance).

The Challenge: Can you see patterns in where high-salary players (big dots) cluster?
Question: What simple rules might divide players into salary groups?

Building Our First Regression Tree

  • Root split: Years < 5 (rookies vs experienced players)
  • Second split: Among experienced players, Hits < 118
  • Three salary groups: Rookies, experienced/low-hits, experienced/high-hits

Visualizing the Tree’s Solution

How Decision Trees Work: The Algorithm

Decision Trees use recursive binary splitting to partition the predictor space:

For Regression Trees:

  1. At each step: Find predictor \(X_j\) and cutpoint \(s\) that minimizes RSS: \[\sum_{i: x_i \in R_1} (y_i - \hat{y}_{R_1})^2 + \sum_{i: x_i \in R_2} (y_i - \hat{y}_{R_2})^2\]

  2. Split regions: \(R_1 = \{X|X_j < s\}\) and \(R_2 = \{X|X_j \geq s\}\)

  3. Predict: Use mean of training observations in each terminal region

Tree Algorithm Process:

  • Top-down: Start with all data, recursively split
  • Greedy: Choose best split at each step (not globally optimal)
  • Binary: Each split creates exactly two branches
  • Stopping criteria: Min observations per node, complexity parameter, max depth

What about classification?

Two Types of Decision Trees Based on Outcome Variable:

Regression Trees (What we just saw):

  • Outcome: Continuous variable (salary, price, temperature)
  • Prediction: Mean of observations in each leaf node
  • Splitting criterion: Minimize RSS (Residual Sum of Squares)
  • Example: Predicting baseball player salaries

Classification Trees (Coming up next):

  • Outcome: Categorical variable (yes/no, pass/fail, low/medium/high)
  • Prediction: Most common class in each leaf node
  • Splitting criterion: Minimize node impurity (Gini Index or Cross-entropy)
    • Gini Index: \(G = \sum_{k=1}^{K} \hat{p}_{mk}(1 - \hat{p}_{mk})\)
    • Cross-entropy: \(D = -\sum_{k=1}^{K} \hat{p}_{mk} \log \hat{p}_{mk}\)
  • Example: Predicting credit card default (Default vs No Default)

Understanding the Gini Index

The Goal: Create nodes that are as “pure” as possible (contain mostly one class)

  • Example: What question to ask if I want to predict econ major?

Gini Index Formula (Simplified for Two Classes):

For binary classification with classes “yes” and “no”:

\[G = 2p(1-p)\]

  • where \(p\) = proportion of “yes” observations
  • and \((1-p)\) = proportion of “no” observations

Intuitive Examples:

##              Scenario Prop_Yes Prop_No Gini_Index
## 1      Perfect Purity      0.0     1.0       0.00
## 2      Worst Impurity      0.5     0.5       0.50
## 3 Moderate Impurity 1      0.7     0.3       0.42
## 4 Moderate Impurity 2      0.2     0.8       0.32
  • Goal is to find splits that have the smallest \(G\)

Classification Performance Metrics

Decision trees follow the same evaluation framework as logistic regression, k-NN, or any other classifier:

  1. Split data into training and test sets
  2. Train model on training data
  3. Make predictions on test data
  4. Build confusion matrix from predictions vs actual
##          Actual
## Predicted   No  Yes
##       No  2860   71
##       Yes   26   43
  1. Calculate performance metrics from confusion matrix
##                 Metric Value
## 1             Accuracy 0.968
## 2            Precision 0.623
## 3 Sensitivity (Recall) 0.377
## 4          Specificity 0.991
## 5             F1 Score 0.470

Tree Complexity and When Trees Struggle

  • Trees can easily overfit because they are so flexible

Tree Algorithms: Stopping Criteria

rpart.control() Parameters:

  • cp: Complexity parameter (minimum improvement required for split)
  • minsplit: Minimum observations required to attempt split
  • maxdepth: Maximum tree depth
  • Tradeoff: Early stopping vs overfitting

Understanding Tree Predictions

How rpart Makes Predictions:

  • Each internal node tests one variable against a threshold
  • Follow the appropriate branch based on the test result
  • Continue until reaching a terminal (leaf) node
  • Use the majority class (or mean) in that leaf as the prediction

Tree Implementation in R: Practical Guide

# Basic syntax
rpart(formula, data, method, control = rpart.control())

# Method options:
# "anova" - regression trees (continuous outcome)
# "class" - classification trees (categorical outcome)

# Controlling complexity
rpart.control(cp = 0.01,        # Complexity parameter (lower = more complex)
              minsplit = 20,     # Min observations to attempt split
              maxdepth = 10)     # Maximum tree depth

# Visualization
rpart.plot(tree_model, type = 4, extra = 2)  # Professional tree plots

# Predictions
predict(tree_model, newdata, type = "class") # Classifications
predict(tree_model, newdata, type = "prob")  # Class probabilities
predict(tree_model, newdata)                 # Regression (default)

Trees vs Linear Models: When to Use Each

  • Linear separable data: Logistic regression excels with straight-line boundaries
  • Non-linear patterns: Decision trees capture complex, rectangular regions naturally
  • Interpretability: Trees provide if-then rules, logistic gives linear coefficients
  • This example: Tree clearly outperforms logistic regression on non-linear boundary!

Building Intuition: Manual Tree Construction

# Calculate RSS for different potential splits on Years
years_splits <- c(2.5, 3.5, 4.5, 5.5, 6.5);rss_results <- numeric(length(years_splits))
for(i in seq_along(years_splits)) {
  split_val <- years_splits[i]
  # Split data
  left_group <- Hitters$LogSalary[Hitters$Years < split_val]
  right_group <- Hitters$LogSalary[Hitters$Years >= split_val]
  # Calculate RSS for each group
  left_rss <- sum((left_group - mean(left_group))^2)
  right_rss <- sum((right_group - mean(right_group))^2)
  # Total RSS
  rss_results[i] <- left_rss + right_rss
}
##   Years_Split Total_RSS   Best_Split
## 1         2.5    137.93             
## 2         3.5    108.40             
## 3         4.5    105.37  <-- MINIMUM
## 4         5.5    125.50             
## 5         6.5    143.48
  • Decision trees tests all possible splits and chooses the one that minimizes our criteria
  • Very powerful algorithm but can be computationally intensive for large datasets

Limitations of Single Decision Trees

High Variance Problem:

  • Small changes in data can produce very different decision trees
  • Example: Remove a few observations → completely different splits
  • This makes decision trees unstable for prediction

Other Limitations:

  • Linear relationships: Need many splits to approximate
  • Biased splits: Favor predictors with more possible cut points
  • Overfitting: Deep decision trees memorize training data
